{{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}

The '''Australian Height Datum''' is a [[geodetic datum]] for [[altitude]] measurement in [[Australia]]. According to [[Geoscience Australia]], "In 1971 the [[Sea Level|mean sea level]] for 1966-1968 was assigned the value of 0.000m on the Australian Height Datum at thirty [[tide gauge]]s around the coast of the Australian continent. The resulting datum surface, with minor modifications in two metropolitan areas, has been termed the Australian Height Datum (AHD) and was adopted by the National Mapping Council as the datum to which all vertical control for mapping (and other surveying functions) is to be referred."<ref>[http://www.ga.gov.au/earth-monitoring/geodesy/geodetic-datums/australian-height-datum-ahd.html Australian Height Datum] Geoscience Australia</ref><ref>[http://www.bom.gov.au/lam/glossary/apagegl.shtml BoM glossary]</ref><ref>{{Citation | last1=Roelse|first1= A. | last2=Granger|first2= H. W. | last3=Graham|first3= J. W. | title=The adjustment of the Australian levelling survey 1970-1971 | edition=2nd|publication-date=1975 | publisher=Dept. of National Development, Australia |  url=ftp://ftp.ga.gov.au/geodesy-outgoing/miscell/AHD_Docs/DNM_Tech_Report_12_%202nd_%20ed.PDF| accessdate=15 April 2017 }}</ref>

