{{Infobox building | name = Green Spine | alternate_names = | building_type = | architectural_style = | classification = | location = [[Melbourne, Australia]] | address = | location_city = | location_country = | est_completion = | topped_out_date = | completion_date = | closing_date = | cost = | height = {{convert|360|m|ft}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.archdaily.com/900424/this-week-in-architecture-australias-tallest-tower-and-questions-about-infrastructure|title=This Week in Architecture: Australia's Tallest Tower and Questions about Infrastructure|last=Allen|first=Katherine|date=18 August 2018|publisher=ArchDaily|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> | architectural = | tip = | antenna_spire = | material = | size = | floor_area = | architect = UNStudio and Cox Architecture }} '''Green Spine''' (originally known as '''Southbank''') is a two-building development proposed for [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]] developed by [[Beulah International]] and designed by architectural firms [[UNStudio]] and [[Philip Cox|Cox Architecture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/08/15/unstudio-cox-melbourne-australias-tallest-building-architecture/|title=UNStudio to design Australia's tallest building|last=Block|first=India|date=15 August 2018|publisher=DeZeen|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> The site currently hosts a BMW dealership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/green-spine-southern-hemispheres-tallest-skyscraper-2018-8|title=The stunning 'Green Spine' will be Melbourne's newest skyscraper -- and the Southern Hemisphere's tallest|last=Farquhar|first=Peter|date=15 August 2018|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> If completed as planned, the building will become the tallest in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theurbandeveloper.com/articles/beulah-begins-construction-on-200m-paragon-development|title=Construction Under Way on Beulah’s Latest Project|last=Tabet|first=Ted|date=2 October 2018|publisher=The Urban Developer|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>
==Southbank competition== Beulah International conducted a contest to determine the architect for the project, and dubbed the competition "Southbank by Beulah". All six solicited bids involved two architectural firms, and partnerships included [[Bjarke Ingels|BIG Architects]] and [[Fender Katsalidis]], [[MAD Studio]] and [[Elenberg Fraser]], and [[Woods Bagot]] and [[Winy Maas|MVRDV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/07/27/big-mad-mvrdv-oma-unstudio-and-coop-himmelblau-shortlisted-melbourne-skyscraper/|title=BIG, MAD, MVRDV and OMA on shortlist to design Australia's tallest building|last=Block|first=India|date=27 July 2018|publisher=DeZeen|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> The collaborative bid by [[UNStudio]] and [[Philip Cox|Cox Architecture]] ultimately secured the commission.
