{{short description|A guyot of the Hawaiian-Emperor seamount chain in the Pacific Ocean}}
'''Jingū Seamount''', also called '''Jingū Guyot''', is a [[guyot]] of the [[Hawaiian-Emperor seamount chain]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]]. It erupted 55 million years ago. The seamount is elongated in structure, running North-South, and has an oval shaped crater in the center, which is evidence of collapse when above sea level.<ref>[http://www.volcanolive.com/jingu.html Jingu Seamount - John Search]</ref><ref name=deepsea_v55c40 />

The seamount was named in 1954 by [[Robert S. Dietz]],<ref name=deepsea_v55c40 /> after Japanese [[Empress Jingū]].<ref name=deepsea_v55c40>{{cite book |title=Initial Reports of the Deep Sea Drilling Project |last1=Calgue |first1=David A. |last2=Dalrymple |first2=G. Brent |last3=Greene |first3=H. Gary |last4=Wald |first4=Donna |last5=Kono |first5=Masaru |last6=Kroenke |first6=Loren W. |chapter=40. Bathymetry of the Emperor Seamounts |chapterurl=http://www.deepseadrilling.org/55/volume/dsdp55_40.pdf |volume=55 |pages=846–847 |year=1980 |publisher=[[US Government Printing Office]] |place=[[Washington, DC]] |lccn=74-603338 |accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref>

